Set X, y(y has two kinds: binary and 5-level)¶

In [1111]:
# set X, y
X = mat.drop('G3', axis = 1)
y = mat['G3']

binary_y = []
five_level_y = []

# set binary y and 5-level y
for num in y:
    if(num >= 10):
        binary_y.append('pass')
    else:
        binary_y.append('fail')
    if(num >= 16 and num <=20):
        five_level_y.append('A')
    elif(num >= 14 and num <=15):
        five_level_y.append('B')
    elif(num >= 12 and num <=13):
        five_level_y.append('C')
    elif(num >= 10 and num <=11):
        five_level_y.append('D')
    else:
        five_level_y.append('F')
        
binary_y = pd.DataFrame(binary_y)
five_level_y = pd.DataFrame(five_level_y)

Model Construction: Decision Tree without PCA for binary classification¶

In [1113]:
from sklearn import tree

DecisionTreeNPCA_model=tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()
In [1114]:
import statistics
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics._classification import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics._classification import recall_score
from sklearn.metrics._classification import precision_score
from tabulate import tabulate

folds = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3)

binary_label = ['pass', 'fail']

accscores = []
recscores = []
prescores = []

cm_holder = []

for train_index, test_index in folds.split(X,binary_y):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[test_index], \
                                       binary_y.iloc[train_index], binary_y.iloc[test_index]
    # test model
    DecisionTreeNPCA_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = DecisionTreeNPCA_model.predict(X_test)
    cm_holder.append(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict, labels = binary_label))
    accscores.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict))  
    recscores.append(recall_score(y_test, y_predict, average='macro'))  
    prescores.append(precision_score(y_test, y_predict, average='macro'))
In [1115]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# results: confusion matrix
ma = sum(cm_holder)/3
plt.figure(figsize = (16,5))
sns.heatmap(ma, square= False, annot=True, cbar= False)
plt.xlabel("predicted value")
plt.ylabel("true value")
plt.show()

# results: accuracy
accuracy = statistics.mean(accscores)

# results: sensitivity(recall)
recall = statistics.mean(recscores)

# results: precision
precision = statistics.mean(prescores)

# draw table with accuracy, recall, precision
data = [[accuracy, recall, precision]]

headers = ["accuracy", "recall", "precision"]

print(tabulate(data, headers= headers, tablefmt= "grid"))

Model Construction: Random forest without PCA for binary classification¶

Note: difference between K-fold cross-validation and Random Forest¶

  • K-fold cross validation: 一種驗證方式。將給定的dataset分成k份，每次取k-1份進行training(fit)，剩餘的1份用於testing(predict)，此動作重複k次，每次使用不同的testing，最後將score平均即為該model的performance。
  • Random forest: 一種classifier。從給定的dataset中選定bootstrap(同一資料可被重複取用)，再從bootstrap data中隨機選取features(或samples)，生成tree，重複上列動作生成多棵tree。Predict由多棵樹共同決定，計算每棵樹的結果，最高票數的label則為predict.

Model Construction: Decision Tree with PCA for binary classification¶

DecisionTreePCA_model=tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()
In [1140]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA


folds = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3)

accscores15 = []
recscores15 = []
prescores15 = []

cm_holder15 = []


scaler = StandardScaler()

for train_index, test_index in folds.split(X,binary_y):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[test_index], \
                                       binary_y.iloc[train_index], binary_y.iloc[test_index]
    
    # Fit on training set only.
    scaler.fit(X_train)

    # Apply transform to both the training set and the test set.
    X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)
    X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)
    
    # Make an instance of the Model
    pca=PCA(n_components='mle')
    
    # fitting PCA on the training set only.
    pca.fit(X_train)

    # dimensional reduction
    X_train = pca.transform(X_train)
    X_test = pca.transform(X_test)
        
    # test model
    DecisionTreePCA_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = DecisionTreePCA_model.predict(X_test)
    cm_holder15.append(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict, labels = binary_label))
    accscores15.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict))  
    recscores15.append(recall_score(y_test, y_predict, average='macro'))  
    prescores15.append(precision_score(y_test, y_predict, average='macro'))

| precision  |  0.6782277246594456  |  0.35729534762673776  |
+------------+----------------------+-----------------------+

從上圖的表來看，PCA對model的performance影響巨大，我們可以分項比較without PCA和with PCA的表現：

  • 在相同model下：有PCA時performance皆呈現下降趨勢，而對於有更多label的5-level classification來說，下降的趨勢更劇烈
  • 在不同model下：受影響的程度Decision tree > Random forest > KNN, 而performance則是Recall > Precision > Accuracy

Describe the difference between boosting and bagging¶

Both used in esemble learning, there are different in three categories

  • How to make classification
    • Boosting: Making a lot of 'weak learners'(usually stumps = root with only two leaves), and do classification with these
    • Bagging: Making a lot of trees, and do classification with them
  • Voting
    • Boosting: Uses weighed voting, stumps may have different weights
    • Bagging: Uses normal voting, every tree has equal say
  • Relations in between
    • Boosting: The stump order matters in boosting, since each stump take in account of the previous stump's mistake
    • Bagging: Every tree is independent

from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap

def plot_decision_regions(X, y, classifier, test_idx=None, resolution=0.02):
        # Create color maps
        cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#AAAAFF'])
        cmap_bold = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#0000FF'])
              
        # Plot the decision boundary. For that, we will assign a color to each
        # point in the mesh [x_min, x_max]x[y_min, y_max].
        x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
        y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
        xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, resolution),
                             np.arange(y_min, y_max, resolution))
        Z = classifier.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])

        # Put the result into a color plot
        Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
        fig = plt.figure()
        plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z, cmap=cmap_light)

        # Plot also the training points, x-axis = 'G1', y-axis = 'G2'
        plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cmap_bold, edgecolor='k', s=30)   
        plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max())
        plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())
        plt.title("0/1 outcome classification (k = 10)")
        plt.show()
